2085	  \cref{def:gr_transition} (a point of \(U^I_J\) and its image under
2086	  \(\theta_{I,J}\) are the two coordinates of a point of the diagonal). We claim
2087	  \(\delta_{I,J}\) is surjective. Its image contains all entries of \(X^I\)
2088	  (from the first factor). From the second factor it contains the entries of
2089	  \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\); taking the \(I\)-minor of this matrix, and using
2090	  \(X^I_I = 1_{d\times d}\), the image contains the entries of \((X^I_J)^{-1}\),
2091	  and in particular
2092	  \[
2093	    \delta_{I,J}(1 \otimes P^J_I) = \det\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1}\bigr) = 1/P^I_J .
2094	  \]
